properties.name: South Middle Atlas Frontal Thrust
properties.notes: Blind thrust; anticline is very well exposed. Likely merges with South Middle Atlas Thrust at depth.

properties.name: Beni-Mellal Fault
properties.notes: Lithologic boundary that likely corresponds to older rift-bounding normal fault. Could be steep, could be shallow.

properties.name: Tigheboula Thrust
properties.notes: frontal nappe-bounding thrust to main Beni-Mellal thrust

properties.name: South Middle Atlas Rangefront Thrust
properties.notes: Rangefront thrust; may not be currently active, but basinward blind thrusts probably sole in at ~1 km depth or so. May be steep reactivated rift-bounding normal fault, or may be shallower thrust.

properties.notes: Blind thrust and anticline.
Possible blind thrust in basin.

properties.name: Kasbah Thrust
properties.notes: Some surface rupturing during the 1960 Agadir earthqake, which may or may not have been on a ramp of this fault at depth to the north.

properties.name: South Atlas Thrust

properties.name: South Atlas Thrust
properties.notes: No clear rupture but some possibilities. Also some evidence of folding/ blind thrusting into the basin.
Spotted on DEM and Google Earth.

properties.name: North Atlas Fault
properties.notes: Rangefront fault, mostly (some deformed rocks to north). No idea if it's active or where the trace is, mapped mostly from DEM.
Front of uplifted fan basinward of the North Atlas Fault.  Looks more active than rangefront fault but this is a tricky orogen.

properties.name: North Atlas Fault
properties.notes: Strange triangular bedrock salient at North Atlas rangefront. Possibly a nappe.

properties.name: Nekor Fault
properties.notes: sinistral-normal in NE, sinistral-reverse in SW

properties.name: Fez Fault
properties.reference: DEM, drawn approx. on many maps
properties.notes: Signs of active deformation and GPS gradient at approx. location of frontal thrust of the Rif belt. The Rif structures look very thin-skinned, however, some of the structures observed in the DEM look to be strike-slip. Things are unclear.

Possible trace observed by linking geomorphic features on DEM. Essentially at the southern Rif thrust front, but may not be reactivating old thrust. Some GPS velocity gradient. City of Fez is at western end, should be a primary target of field investigation.

properties.name: Sanhaja Fault
properties.notes: Very well expressed lineament in DEM; worth investigation
westernmost Rif thrust. It's got to be somewhere and this is a convenient topographic escarpemnt.
Westernmost Rif thrust; hard to place trace exactly but seismicity and GPS stop here
Koulali has it mapped (from earlier sources?) but does not draw a GPS block boundary along it. Nonetheless there  is a ~1mm/yr velocity gradient across it.
